Since you&#39;re using that key in an HTML tag, hiding it from Git commit won&#39;t make your key safe from public access because anyways on production the key will be publicly accessible since the clients can see HTML code that the server is sending.

If you just want to make sure that the key won&#39;t be committed to Git, then I can think of two methods in that case.

1. Keep the key in a separate file (like the .env that we usually use with nodejs), read the file contents using Java (Since you said Java is used instead of nodejs), and while rendering the webpage simply put that key in the output.

2. Create a javascript file and keep your key in that script file (assign it to a variable)
And then in your HTML file you can simply write a JavaScript code like this:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;env.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;script&gt;
        var s = document.createElement(&quot;script&quot;);
        s.type = &quot;text/javascript&quot;;
        s.src = &quot;https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=&quot;+myKey+&quot;&amp;callback=initMap&quot;;
        $(&quot;head&quot;).append(s);
    &lt;/script&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Make sure that you&#39;re creating a variable with the name &quot;myKey&quot; in your env.js file.

Now you can simply add your env.js file to .gitignore

